I disagree about our society being packed full of restrictive laws.  I do not feel restricted.

&quot;Ask Switzerland&quot;
Swiss here. We have guns to protect our governement, not to protect ourselves from the governement or from trespassers. It&#39;s a very different situation.
Given Swiss history (individual nation-states joining into 1 federation), we may tend to see the collective governement as something good for individuals, a guarantee of our rights rather than a threat to our freedom. I think this was traditionnaly the case in most of Europe, but has been changing since the turn of the century.

While protecting one&#39;s self is important, I find it hard to believe that someone needs military grade weapons with 50 round clips. From a 5-year analysis of home invasions:
&quot;The average and median number of shots fired was 2. When more than 2 shots were fired, it generally appeared that the defender’s initial response was to fire until empty. &quot;
So defending one&#39;s self does not require military grade weapons, just a little handgun.

&quot;Because protection is prevention, and prevention is the best cure. If a burglar thinks you might own a weapon, they will likely not break into your house.&quot;
Wrong. If a burglar thinks you might own a weapon, they will bring their own weapon.

Burglars act on desperation, not fear. Threatening a burglar with a deadly weapon is an easy way to escalate a situation into a deadly one. And proliferating deadly weapons will only heighten criminals&#39; vigilance, but won&#39;t prevent their crimes.

